(fifthQuint)Stem Cell Transplant for Immunologic or Histiocytic Disorders.

 Prior to transplantation, subjects will receive Melphalan, Fludarabine and Anti-Thymocyte Globulin (ATG) or Campath.

 These three drugs are being given to subjects to help the new stem cells take and grow.

 On the day of transplantation, subjects will receive stem cells transfused via intravenous (IV) catheter.

 After stem cell transplantation, subjects will be given Cyclosporin A (CsA) and mycophenolate mofetil (MMF) to reduce the risk of graft-versus-host disease, the complication that occurs when the donor's stem cells react against the patient.

